<br>
Some raids most of the time is getting people there, grouped, and buffed.  Since that overhead cost is fixed if you can do a longer raid it is more efficient.  <br>
<br>
For a single target raid, VS, Trak, Gore, etc. you can log on and in 2 hours have found out about it, mobilized, grouped, buffed, won, divied up the loot, TL/port, and log off.<br>
<br>
Other raids such as WW dragons, ToV armor farming, etc. often go until you lose the necessary number of certain classes (usu clerics it seems).<br>
<br>
Planes raids often go for a full clearing.  Public raids are, um...*cough* usually less than efficient.  They can fail on breaks, have lengthy CRs since they are few, if any, epic clerics/chanters along, and often have less experienced pullers.  All of this results in a *long* process.<br>
<br>
For example, a fairly recent public hate raid took a tad over 7 hours (with 12 groups) and had *almost* cleared the first floor.  Last decent guild raid I did up there cleared it in about 3 or so (with 5-6 groups).<br>
<br>
The BEST thing to do is always let the RL/GL know how long you can stay in advance.  Don't go to a raid assuming it will only take 2 hours and then realize they aren't even halfway there.  Furthermore it looks bad if you just 'happen' to leave after you have looted.  Most public raid leaders expect that you will stay to the end, *especially* if you loot.  If you tell them you have to go at 11, don't hang around and hope to loot something till midnight and then leave.<br>
<br>
In general, be prompt, leave with full notice, LISTEN and follow directions.<br>
<br>
FYI, very, very rarely do I ever play for more than 8 hours.  I usually reach that limit only in WW or ToV settings.  And if you tell the leaders you can come, but can only spend 8 hours and they are mad, well... appologize and find new people to raid with.<br>
<br>
Sure, on a rare day for VP, or NToV the guild may want to do a 12 hour run, but that is the exception.  <br>
<br>
Hope that helped.<br>
<br>
<br>
Kether<br>
